definition.value: Developmental organism from fertilization to 8 weeks of gestation.
The orifice existing between the rectum and the anus.
Any of various groupings of muscle fibers.
Smooth muscle fiber group arranged in sheets.
Muscle fiber group which consists of non-striated muscle fibers invested by connective tissue fibers.
A tubular structure that transports secreted or excreted substances.
Organ segment which consists of a wall lined with epithelial cells and which encloses a lumen.

label.value: set of hair of labial part of mouth

definition.value: Individual hairs on the labial part of the mouth taken together as a set.
Anatomical structure which is the aggregate material substance of an individual member of the human species.
A period of time with fixed, well-defined limits.

label.value: subdivision of wall of head proper

definition.value: Subdivision of cardinal body part, each instance of which is a regional part of some wall of head proper.
Either of the columns of erectile tissue forming the body of the clitoris or penis.
One of the folds of skin which form the inner lips (labia minora) and outer lips (labia majora) on both sides of the vaginal opening.
Any and all borders of the ovary, in particular the mesovarian (or anterior) border and the free (or posterior) border.
One of the poles of the ovary.
A strand of hair that is part of a particular body region.
A mucosa that is part of the vulva.

One of a pair of embryonic tubular structures that extend along the genital ridge and continue toward the cloaca, which in persons assigned female at birth will develop into the vagina, uterus, and fallopian tubes, and which will degenerate and be resorbed in those assigned male at birth.
An organ zone of the body of the uterus.
Anatomical conduit space that connects two adjacent body spaces, surrounded by two or more subdivisions of two or more organs or organ parts.
An anatomical surface which is a subdivision of the surface of the uterus.
A layer of smooth muscle in the urinary tract.
Organ component layer adjacent to serosa of organ. Organ component layer, each instance of which is layer of losse areolar tissue underlying the serosa of sme organ.
Organ component layer that constitutes the outermost layer of an organ.
A part of the system of genitalia.
An external genital phenotype related in some form or fashion to the product and/or maintenance of wolffian gametes or other processes involving wolffian gametes.
The outer organs related to sexual activity and/or reproductive processes.
An external genital phenotype related in some form or fashion to the product and/or maintenance of mllerian gametes or other processes involving mllerian gametes.
The inner organs related to sexual activity and/or reproductive processes.
An internal genital phenotype related in some form or fashion to the product and/or maintenance of mllerian gametes or other processes involving mllerian gametes.
An internal genital phenotype related in some form or fashion to the product and/or maintenance of wolffian gametes or other processes involving wolffian gametes.
A part of the upper respiratory tract. It contains the organ of smell. The term includes the external nose, the nasal cavity, and the paranasal sinuses.
A structure of special sense serving as an organ of the sense of smell and as an entrance to the respiratory tract.
Subdivision of face which consists of skeletal system of nose, all layers superficial to it (integument, mucosa, muscle, connective tissue) and nasal cavity.
The olfactory organ of vertebrates, consisting of nares, olfactory epithelia and the structures and skeletal framework of the nasal cavity.
The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.
The part of the face that is below the eye and to the side of the nose and mouth.
Subdivision of mouth, each instance of which is a regional part of the mouth.
Part of the oral cavity bounded laterally and ventrally by the alveolar arches and their contained teeth. Its roof is formed by the palate and it communicates posteriorly with the oropharynx.

The proximal portion of the digestive tract, containing the oral cavity and bounded by the oral opening. In vertebrates, this extends to the pharynx and includes gums, lips, tongue and parts of the palate. Typically also includes the teeth, except where these occur elsewhere (e.g. pharyngeal jaws) or protrude from the mouth (tusks).

Postnatal anatomical structure, each instance of which has as it direct parts a heterogeneous collection of some instances of two or more subclasses of anatomcial structure, which are spatially related to one another; the collections as a whole does not satisfy the definition of any other subclass of anatomical structure.
Immaterial anatomical entity of one less dimension than the anatomical entity it bounds or demarcates from another anatomical entity.

A filament-like structure consisting of a shaft which projects to the surface of the skin from a root which is softer than the shaft and lodges in the cavity of a hair follicle. It is found on most surfaces of the body.
The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.
Any of the short hairs that grow on the edge of the eyelid.
The hairs which project from the edges of the eyelids.

The eyebrow is an area of thick, delicate hairs above the eye that follows the shape of the lower margin of the brow ridges. Their main function is to protect the eye, but they are also important to human communication and facial expression. It is not uncommon for people to modify their eyebrows by means of hair addition or removal, make up, or piercings.

The collection of hair that grows on the chin, cheeks and neck of human beings. Usually, only pubescent or adult males are able to grow beards. However, women with hirsutism may develop a beard. When differentiating between upper and lower facial hair, a beard specifically includes the moustache, which refers to hair above the upper lip and around it.
A strand of hair that is part of a head.
A strand of hair that is part of a limb.
A strand of hair that is part of an upper limb.
A strand of hair that is part of an lower limb.
A strand of hair that is part of a trunk.
A strand of hair that is part of the pectoral girdle.
A strand of hair that is part of the axilla.
This is not the same as axillary hair found on monocots and mosses.
Hair growing in the pubic area.
Hair growing in the area around the anus.
A horn-like keratin structure covering the dorsal aspect of the terminal phalanges of fingers and toes.
A nail is a horn-like envelope covering the dorsal aspect of the terminal phalanges of fingers and toes in humans, most non-human primates, and a few other mammals.
The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.
